2.43.0
Description: Fix a verification DoS due to a malicious subkey in the keyring
 GnuPG failed to properly validate subkey binding signatures (backsig) and
 usage flags when looking up the public key used to verify an OpenPGP
 signature. An attacker could craft a public key certificate that adds a
 signing subkey copied from another (victim) primary key, without a valid
 backsig binding that subkey to the attacker's own primary key. Once such
 a malicious certificate is imported into the keyring, gpg could end up
 selecting the malicious/unrelated key material when looking up the key
 for a signature made by the victim key, causing verification of
 otherwise-good signatures made with the victim key to spuriously fail
 (a signature verification Denial of Service, CWE-754).
 .
 This patch backports the two upstream commits that fix this issue to
 gnupg2 2.2.27 as shipped in Debian 11 (bullseye):
 .
  * gpg: Fix a verification DoS due to a malicious subkey in the keyring.
    (GnuPG-bug-id 7527) - introduces get_pubkey_bykid()/get_pubkey_for_sig()
    with an r_keyblock out-argument so that signature verification
    (check_signature(), do_check_sig()) always operates on the full,
    correctly-looked-up keyblock of the actual signing key, and requires
    PUBKEY_USAGE_SIG so that a subkey lacking a valid backsig or with bad
    usage flags is skipped during key lookup. Also removes the now
    redundant get_pubkeyblock_for_sig() helper and the check_signature2()
    wrapper naming (folded into check_signature()), and makes key lookups
    used for import/merge (get_keyblock_byfprint_fast()) able to restrict
    matches to the primary key fingerprint only.
  * gpg: Fix regression for the recent malicious subkey DoS fix.
    (GnuPG-bug-id 7547) - follow-up fix adding a PUBKEY_USAGE_VERIFY
    modifier so that expired or revoked signing keys are still found
    during signature verification (previously they could be skipped
    entirely, causing a regression where good signatures from expired
    or revoked keys were reported as having no public key at all
    instead of being correctly flagged as expired/revoked).
